Download the Tarball

https://fermi.gsfc.nasa.gov/ssc/data/analysis/gbm/gspec/gspec-0.9.1.tar.gz

From Site : https://fermi.gsfc.nasa.gov/ssc/data/analysis/gbm/

It should be a file named something like gspec-0.9.1.tar.gz (or whatever the latest version is) sitting in your Downloads folder.


1. Create the Environment

We use Python 3.10. Even though it's modern, we lock Matplotlib to the last version that almost works with this legacy code.
Bash

mamba create -n gbm -c conda-forge python=3.10 tk numpy scipy astropy "matplotlib<3.6" -y

2. Install the Software (The "No-Compiler" Hack)

Activate the environment and install only the Python scripts. This prevents your CachyOS C++ compiler from trying (and failing) to build old libraries.
Bash

mamba activate gbm
cd ~/Downloads
pip install --no-deps gspec-0.9.1.tar.gz

3. Apply the "Surgery" (The Patch)

This command goes into the installed files and renames the outdated Matplotlib components to their modern names so the GUI doesn't crash on launch.
Bash

find /home/void/miniforge3/envs/gbm/lib/python3.10/site-packages/gbm -type f -name "*.py" -exec sed -i 's/NavigationToolbar2TkAgg/NavigationToolbar2Tk/g' {} +

4. The Fix: One More "Surgery"

We need to run another sed command to find every instance where the code says .show() and change it to .draw().

Make sure your gbm environment is active and run this command:
Bash

find /home/void/miniforge3/envs/gbm/lib/python3.10/site-packages/gbm -type f -name "*.py" -exec sed -i 's/plotter.canvas.show()/plotter.canvas.draw()/g' {} +

Why this works:

This specifically targets the line mentioned in your traceback (File ".../dataviewer.py", line 393). By changing it to draw(), the GUI will finally be able to communicate with the modern Matplotlib library on your system.

4. The "Stacked" Launch Sequence

Because gspec needs to talk to xspec (which is in your henv environment), you must load both at once.

Run this every time you want to use it:
Bash

# Load HEASoft first
mamba activate henv

# Layer GBM on top
mamba activate --stack gbm

# Launch the tool
gspec

Why this is necessary:

The gbm_data_tools were written years ago. Since then, the Matplotlib developers renamed NavigationToolbar2TkAgg to NavigationToolbar2Tk. Most people on older Linux versions (like your Kubuntu 22.04) don't see this because they are using older libraries.

On CachyOS, you are "too fast" for the old code, so we have to manually edit the software's source code (via sed) to make it compatible with 2026 standards.
